1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,025
In this lesson, we're going to talk about adding color as an encoding.

2
00:00:05,025 --> 00:00:09,000
Now, color is a natural encoding regime for additional variables

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,065
and it's easily supported by both Matplotlib and Seaborn.

4
00:00:13,065 --> 00:00:20,805
To get started, let's begin by doing our normal imports and also importing our data set.

5
00:00:20,805 --> 00:00:26,250
There are many ways to add color to Seaborn plots and this lesson we're going to use

6
00:00:26,250 --> 00:00:32,520
facet grid and we're going to specifically set for our facet grid a hue parameter.

7
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:36,820
In this case, we're going to set it to be transmission type.

8
00:00:36,820 --> 00:00:41,300
We're going to plot specifically regression plot

9
00:00:41,300 --> 00:00:46,630
looking at fuel efficiency versus engine size.

10
00:00:46,630 --> 00:00:53,690
Note that the hue parameter sets the transmission type that we're interested in.

11
00:00:53,690 --> 00:00:59,590
Also, hue order allows us to specify the order that would like to use.

12
00:00:59,590 --> 00:01:02,855
Note also that because we only have a single plot,

13
00:01:02,855 --> 00:01:07,535
I decided to set the aspect ratio to 1.5,

14
00:01:07,535 --> 00:01:09,500
which gives us a larger plot,

15
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:12,385
50% longer than it is tall.

16
00:01:12,385 --> 00:01:15,930
Now, let's look at vehicle class instead.

17
00:01:15,930 --> 00:01:18,600
Vehicle class is an ordered variable so

18
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:23,410
the qualitative palette doesn't work quite as well instead,

19
00:01:23,410 --> 00:01:26,165
we should specify a sequential palette.

20
00:01:26,165 --> 00:01:30,265
This can be set through facet grids with the palette parameter.

21
00:01:30,265 --> 00:01:35,135
Also note that we can use the same strings as in Matplotlib in this case,

22
00:01:35,135 --> 00:01:37,465
I'll use verity reverse.

23
00:01:37,465 --> 00:01:40,685
This palette not only goes from light to dark,

24
00:01:40,685 --> 00:01:43,490
but it also has a good range of hues to further

25
00:01:43,490 --> 00:01:47,860
discriminate between the various vehicle classes.

26
00:01:47,860 --> 00:01:50,795
If instead we have a numeric variable,

27
00:01:50,795 --> 00:01:52,820
such as CO_2 emissions,

28
00:01:52,820 --> 00:01:56,105
we should not just set the variable and the hue parameter,

29
00:01:56,105 --> 00:02:01,745
since facet grids only expect to facet across categorical variables.

30
00:02:01,745 --> 00:02:04,595
If we do that, we're going to get a messy legend with

31
00:02:04,595 --> 00:02:07,960
one color for every unique CO_2 value.

32
00:02:07,960 --> 00:02:13,955
Instead, we should just use the basic Matplotlib scatter function to create our plot.

33
00:02:13,955 --> 00:02:16,730
We lose the convenient jitter in this case,

34
00:02:16,730 --> 00:02:18,770
but there's an interaction in

35
00:02:18,770 --> 00:02:22,820
the color parameters that make coloring by value hard to do.

36
00:02:22,820 --> 00:02:29,180
With scatter adding a third numeric variable is as simple as setting the C parameter,

37
00:02:29,180 --> 00:02:30,875
which stands for color.

38
00:02:30,875 --> 00:02:36,380
We can also set our own color palette using the CMAP parameter.

39
00:02:36,380 --> 00:02:39,275
Finally, for the color bar,

40
00:02:39,275 --> 00:02:46,260
we wanted to add a label to that also to make it clear what we are seeing on this axis.

